  <h2 class="slide-title anim">LNS Exact Core — Iterative Improvement</h2>
  <p class="slide-sub anim">Large Neighborhood Search: refine the Canonical solution with exact CP-SAT on high-pressure sub-neighborhoods.</p>

  <div class="grid-2 anim" style="max-width:960px">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Algorithm Flow</div>
      <div class="step-row"><span class="step-num">1</span><span class="step-text">Start from <strong>Canonical Hybrid</strong> solution as warm start</span></div>
      <div class="step-row"><span class="step-num">2</span><span class="step-text">Rank all apps by <strong>search pressure</strong> score</span></div>
      <div class="step-row"><span class="step-num">3</span><span class="step-text">Select top-K apps as the <strong>neighborhood</strong> to re-optimize</span></div>
      <div class="step-row"><span class="step-num">4</span><span class="step-text">Fix all other apps, run <strong>CP-SAT exactly</strong> on neighborhood</span></div>
      <div class="step-row"><span class="step-num">5</span><span class="step-text"><strong>Accept</strong> if better; repeat until no improvement or time limit</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Search Pressure Ranking</div>
      <ul class="fancy">
        <li><strong>×3 weight</strong> — app involved in active cross-QM flows (most likely to benefit from move)</li>
        <li><strong>×2 weight</strong> — app on most-loaded queue manager (load balancing opportunity)</li>
        <li><strong>×5 weight</strong> — enterprise-critical / PCI / publicly-accessible app (risky, kept stable)</li>
        <li><strong>×1 weight</strong> — highly connected apps (many producer/consumer relationships)</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="card-title">Why LNS?</div>
      <ul class="fancy">
        <li>Pure CP-SAT doesn't scale — LNS decomposes the problem</li>
        <li>Retains provable optimality <em>within</em> each neighborhood</li>
        <li>Dramatically better than pure greedy on large instances</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

